<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-593-126  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 593 126.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  July 9 1990 n3168 p69(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>In Korea, all circuits are go; the chip industry is hot - but itcould stumble without more Randamp;D. (Science and Technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Neff, Robet; Nakarmi, Laxmi; Brandt, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Korea has established itself as the world's third largestsemiconductor producer behind the US and Japan.andP;  Chipmakers inKorea are focusing on the high-volume DRAM markets and Seoul'sSsangyong Research Institute projects that Korea will capture 20percent of 1991's global market for 1M-bit DRAMs.andP;  SamsungElectronics Co, the leading Korean chipmaker, is about a yearbehind Japan in DRAMs.andP;  Even so, it will take a considerableamount of time before Korea poses a threat to the US and Japan inother area of semiconductor production.andP;  Korea is slowly movinginto microprocessors and more profitable chips and is spending asmall percentage of its profits on research and development.andP;  TheUS has made arrangements with a number of Korean companies for theproduction of semiconductor chips and the technology transfercould, ironically, give Korea a stronger competitive edge over theUS.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     KoreaSemiconductor industryDRAMMarket ShareTechnology TransferResearch and DevelopmentCompetition.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Korea's drive in chips is starting to pay off. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>